d Matthew Lovett-Barron and Moriel Zelikowsky},\n booktitle = {Neuron},\n journal = {Neuron},\n pages = {2545-2570},\n title = {The emergence and influence of internal states},\n volume = {110},\n year = {2022}\n}\n"}, "referenceCount": 358, "publicationDate": "2022-05-01", "s2FieldsOfStudy": [{"source": "external", "category": "Medicine"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Biology"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Psychology"}], "publicationTypes": ["Review", "JournalArticle"], "publicationVenue": {"id": "7a61412a-9a9a-487d-9613-5a1fbd879c9d", "url": "https://www.cell.com/neuron/home", "issn": "0896-6273", "name": "Neuron", "type": "journal", "alternate_urls": ["http://www.cell.com/neuron/home", "http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/journal/08966273", "http://www.neuron.org/"]}, "influentialCitationCount": 0}', '2023-01-27 11:00:52.840030', '2023-01-27 11:00:52.840030', 'The emergence and influence of internal states', 2022, false, null, null, null, null);
INSERT INTO public.paper (paper_id, s2ag_json_text, created, updated, title, pub_year, key_paper, pdf_url, can_get_pdf, local_pdf_location, notes) VALUES ('c189e808578b1d2757ba001011afd8c9f226fd50', '{"url": "https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/c189e808578b1d2757ba001011afd8c9f226fd50", "year": 2022, "title": "The Neuromodulatory Basis of Aggression: Lessons From the Humble Fruit Fly", "venue": "Frontiers in Behavioral Neuroscience", "authors": [{"name": "Caroline B. Palavicino-Maggio", "authorId": "1401450057"}, {"name": "Saheli Sengupta", "authorId": "24941355"}], "journal": {"name": "Frontiers in Behavioral Neuroscience", "volume": "16"}, "paperId": "c189e808578b1d2757ba001011afd8c9f226fd50", "abstract": "Aggression is an intrinsic trait that organisms of almost all species, humans included, use to get access to food, shelter, and mating partners. To maximize fitness in the wild, an organism must vary the intensity of aggression toward the same or different stimuli. How much of this variation is genetic and how much is externally induced, is largely unknown but is likely to be a combination of both. Irrespective of the source, one of the principal physiological mechanisms altering the aggression intensity involves neuromodulation. Any change or variation in aggression intensity is most likely governed by a complex interaction of several neuromodulators acting via a meshwork of neural circuits. Resolving aggression-specific neural circuits in a mammalian model has proven challenging due to the highly complex nature of the mammalian brain. In that regard, the fruit fly model Drosophila melanogaster has provided insights into the circuit-driven mechanisms of aggression regulation and its underlying neuromodulatory basis. Despite morphological dissimilarities, the fly brain shares striking similarities with the mammalian brain in genes, neuromodulatory systems, and circuit-organization, making the findings from the fly model extremely valuable for understanding the fundamental circuit logic of human aggression. This review discusses our current understanding of how neuromodulators regulate aggression based on findings from the fruit fly model. We specifically focus on the roles of Serotonin (5-HT), Dopamine (DA), Octopamine (OA), Acetylcholine (ACTH), Sex Peptides (SP), Tachykinin (TK), Neuropeptide F (NPF), and Drosulfakinin (Dsk) in fruit fly male and female aggression.", "citations": [], "externalIds": {"DOI": "10.3389/fnbeh.2022.836666", "PubMed": "35517573", "CorpusId": 248231301, "PubMedCentral": "9062135"}, "isOpenAccess": true, "citationCount": 0, "fieldsOfStudy": ["Medicine"], "openAccessPdf": {"url": "https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fnbeh.2022.836666/pdf", "status": "GOLD"}, "citationStyles": {"bibtex": "@[''Review'', ''JournalArticle'']{Palavicino-Maggio2022TheNB,\n author = {Caroline B. Palavicino-Maggio and Saheli Sengupta},\n booktitle = {Frontiers in Behavioral Neuroscience},\n journal = {Frontiers in Behavioral Neuroscience},\n title = {The Neuromodulatory Basis of Aggression: Lessons From the Humble Fruit Fly},\n volume = {16},\n year = {2022}\n}\n"}, "referenceCount": 219, "publicationDate": "2022-04-18", "s2FieldsOfStudy": [{"source": "external", "category": "Medicine"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Biology"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Psychology"}], "publicationTypes": ["Review", "JournalArticle"], "publicationVenue": {"id": "810ce699-eb80-4394-8aac-a6d3c87840ed", "url": "http://www.frontiersin.org/behavioral_neuroscience", "issn": "1662-5153", "name": "Frontiers in Behavioral Neuroscience", "type": "journal", "alternate_urls": ["http://www.frontiersin.org/behavioralneuroscience/", "https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/behavioral-neuroscience"], "alternate_names": ["Front Behav Neurosci"]}, "influentialCitationCount": 0}', '2023-01-27 11:00:56.478309', '2023-01-27 11:00:56.478309', 'The Neuromodulatory Basis of Aggression: Lessons From the Humble Fruit Fly', 2022, false, null, null, null, null);
