uitry underlying female aggression in Drosophila", "paperId": "df1696050c10fffb86668e9443d39cf72fbddf88"}, {"title": "Fruitless decommissions regulatory elements to implement cell-type-specific neuronal masculinization", "paperId": "f4efa38134797efbd62c8510d370bece9745937b"}, {"title": "A neurogenetic mechanism of experience-dependent suppression of aggression", "paperId": "2912302c8ea94ec38cf68cc0c332457964dd1d3e"}, {"title": "Quantitative comparison of Drosophila behavior annotations by human observers and a machine learning algorithm", "paperId": "3d2cc475c7e29287d943b46ede54fece66b59f92"}, {"title": "Neuronal circuitry underlying female aggression in Drosophila", "paperId": "f18ac21f76fa6b5b89fb45900bc7386ad7e8ceaa"}, {"title": "Sex-determining genes distinctly regulate courtship capability and target preference via sexually dimorphic neurons", "paperId": "3a4e5340f8ad346b518713851dffac0af9716d96"}], "externalIds": {"DOI": "10.7554/eLife.52702", "MAG": "3017332290", "PubMed": "32314957", "CorpusId": 216046197, "PubMedCentral": "7173971"}, "isOpenAccess": false, "citationCount": 19, "fieldsOfStudy": ["Medicine", "Biology"], "openAccessPdf": null, "citationStyles": {"bibtex": "@[''JournalArticle'']{Wohl2020LayeredRO,\n author = {Margot Wohl and Kenichi Ishii and Kenta Asahina},\n booktitle = {eLife},\n journal = {eLife},\n title = {Layered roles of fruitless isoforms in specification and function of male aggression-promoting neurons in Drosophila},\n volume = {9},\n year = {2020}\n}\n"}, "referenceCount": 100, "publicationDate": "2020-04-21", "s2FieldsOfStudy": [{"source": "external", "category": "Medicine"}, {"source": "external", "category": "Biology"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Biology"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Psychology"}], "publicationTypes": ["JournalArticle"], "publicationVenue": {"id": "07365b9a-c0ce-4dd3-b93b-a02e1c81e0c6", "url": "https://epub.uni-regensburg.de/40444/", "issn": "2050-084X", "name": "eLife", "type": "journal", "alternate_urls": ["https://elifesciences.org/", "https://elife.elifesciences.org/", "http://elifesciences.org/"]}, "influentialCitationCount": 0}', '2023-01-27 11:01:58.874368', '2023-01-27 11:01:58.874368', 'Layered roles of fruitless isoforms in specification and function of male aggression-promoting neurons in Drosophila', 2020, false, null, null, null, null);
INSERT INTO public.paper (paper_id, s2ag_json_text, created, updated, title, pub_year, key_paper, pdf_url, can_get_pdf, local_pdf_location, notes) VALUES ('451cfb680942ba0d54234d36efc68da88fa6b8a4', '{"url": "https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/451cfb680942ba0d54234d36efc68da88fa6b8a4", "year": 2022, "title": "Arrestin-mediated desensitization enables intraneuronal olfactory discrimination in Caenorhabditis elegans", "venue": "Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America", "authors": [{"name": "Daniel M. Merritt", "authorId": "153338672"}, {"name": "Isabel MacKay-Clackett", "authorId": "1416910748"}, {"name": "Sylvia M. T. Almeida", "authorId": "2088419103"}, {"name": "Celina Tran", "authorId": "71801352"}, {"name": "Safa Ansar", "authorId": "2088414557"}, {"name": "D. van der Kooy", "authorId": "80919372"}], "journal": {"name": "Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America", "volume": "119"}, "paperId": "451cfb680942ba0d54234d36efc68da88fa6b8a4", "abstract": "Significance Nematode worms rely primarily on olfaction for information about the external world and encode over 1,000 olfactory receptors in their genomes. All olfactory receptors in the worm appear to signal through the same few downstream molecules, and many receptors are expressed in each sensory neuron, raising the question of how worms can distinguish one smell from another. We show that olfactory discrimination occurs through desensitization of stimulated olfactory receptors by the protein arrestin, that the specific receptors to be desensitized are tagged by the protein GRK-1, and that these processes are not required for discrimination between smells sensed by different neurons. This resolves a long-standing question in nematode olfactory biology and reveals a fundamental mechanism of intraneuronal olfactory discrimination.", "citations": [{"title": "Making “Sense” of Ecology from a Genetic Perspective: Caenorhabditis elegans, Microbes and Behavior", "paperId": "18cd1bf55dec55b8951b87c258ea756f7004f96f"}], "externalIds": {"DOI": "10.1073/pnas.2116957119", "PubMed": "35878038", "CorpusId": 251067584, "PubMedCentral": "9351366"}, "isOpenAccess": false, "citationCount": 1, "fieldsOfStudy": ["Medicine"], "openAccessPdf": null, "citationStyles": {"bibtex": "@[''JournalArticle'']{Merritt2022Arrestin-mediatedDE,\n author = {Daniel M. Merritt and Isabel MacKay-Clackett and Sylvia M. T. Almeida and Celina Tran and Safa Ansar and D. van der Kooy},\n booktitle = {Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America},\n journal = {Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America},\n title = {Arrestin-mediated desensitization enables intraneuronal olfactory discrimination in Caenorhabditis elegans},\n volume = {119},\n year = {2022}\n}\n"}, "referenceCount": 32, "publicationDate": "2022-07-25", "s2FieldsOfStudy": [{"source": "external", "category": "Medicine"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Biology"}], "publicationTypes": ["JournalArticle"], "publicationVenue": {"id": "bb95bf2e-8383-4748-bf9d-d6906d091085", "url": "https://www.jstor.org/journal/procnatiacadscie", "issn": "0027-8424", "name": "Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America", "type": "journal", "alternate_urls": ["https://www.pnas.org/", "http://www.jstor.org/journals/00278424.html", "http://www.pnas.org/"], "alternate_names": ["Proc National Acad Sci u s Am"]}, "influentialCitationCount": 0}', '2023-01-27 11:02:02.560273', '2023-01-27 11:02:02.560273', 'Arrestin-mediated desensitization enables intraneuronal olfactory discrimination in Caenorhabditis elegans', 2022, false, null, null, null, null);
INSERT INTO public.paper (paper_id, s2ag_json_text, created, updated, title, pub_year, key_paper, pdf_url, can_get_pdf, local_pdf_location, notes) VALUES ('506662e3afff2be391a28d6ade2bb690e45aa560', '{"url": "https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/506662e3afff2be391a28d6ade2bb690e45aa560", "year": 2022, "title": "Shedding Light on Inter-Individual Variability of Olfactory Circuits in Drosophila", "venue": "Frontiers in Behavioral Neuroscience", "authors": [{"name": "K. Rihani", "authorId": "35663696"}, {"name": "S. Sachse", "authorId": "2285543"}], "journal": {"name": "Frontiers in Behavioral Neuroscience", "volume": "16"}, "paperId": "506662e3afff2be391a28d6ade2bb690e45aa560", "abstract": "Inter-individual differences in behavioral responses, anatomy or functional properties of neuronal populations of animals having the same genotype were for a long time disregarded. The majority of behavioral studies were conducted at a group level, and usually the mean behavior of all individuals was considered. Similarly, in neurophysiological studies, data were pooled and normalized from several individuals. This approach is mostly suited to map and characterize stereotyped neuronal properties between individuals, but lacks the ability to depict inter-individual variability regarding neuronal wiring or physiological characteristics. Recent studies have shown that behavioral biases and preferences to olfactory stimuli can vary significantly among individuals of the same genotype. The origin and the benefit of these diverse “personalities” is still unclear and needs to be further investigated. A perspective taken into account the inter-individual differences is needed to explore the cellular mechanisms underlying this phenomenon. This review focuses on olfaction in the vinegar fly Drosophila melanogaster and summarizes previous and recent studies on odor-guided behavior and the underlying olfactory circuits in the light of inter-individual variability. We address the morphological and physiological variabilities present at each layer of the olfactory circuitry and attempt to link them to individual olfactory behavior. Additionally, we discuss the factors that might influence individuality with regard to olfactory perception.", "citations": [{"title": "Drosophila olfaction: past, present and future", "paperId": "6c32d89c783891ba23860a8999e8150812c99b73"}, {"title": "Probabilistic axon targeting dynamics lead to individualized brain wiring", "paperId": "0356fae88f920b029f41805ae9d6a6eb005a7a75"}, {"title": "A Neuropeptidergic Signaling Pathway for Olfactory Gain Modulation", "paperId": "f99d4048e4f9175f6ec30d75c4757f830a2e76b4"}], "externalIds": {"DOI": "10.3389/fnbeh.2022.835680", "PubMed": "35548690", "CorpusId": 248398612, "PubMedCentral": "9084309"}, "isOpenAccess": true, "citationCount": 3, "fieldsOfStudy": ["Medicine"], "openAccessPdf": {"url": "https://www.frontiersin.org/articles/10.3389/fnbeh.2022.835680/pdf", "status": "GOLD"}, "citationStyles": {"bibtex": "@[''Review'', ''JournalArticle'']{Rihani2022SheddingLO,\n author = {K. Rihani and S. Sachse},\n booktitle = {Frontiers in Behavioral Neuroscience},\n journal = {Frontiers in Behavioral Neuroscience},\n title = {Shedding Light on Inter-Individual Variability of Olfactory Circuits in Drosophila},\n volume = {16},\n year = {2022}\n}\n"}, "referenceCount": 123, "publicationDate": "2022-04-25", "s2FieldsOfStudy": [{"source": "external", "category": "Medicine"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Biology"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Psychology"}], "publicationTypes": ["Review", "JournalArticle"], "publicationVenue": {"id": "810ce699-eb80-4394-8aac-a6d3c87840ed", "url": "http://www.frontiersin.org/behavioral_neuroscience", "issn": "1662-5153", "name": "Frontiers in Behavioral Neuroscience", "type": "journal", "alternate_urls": ["http://www.frontiersin.org/behavioralneuroscience/", "https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/behavioral-neuroscience"], "alternate_names": ["Front Behav Neurosci"]}, "influentialCitationCount": 0}', '2023-01-27 11:02:06.175082', '2023-01-27 11:02:06.175082', 'Shedding Light on Inter-Individual Variability of Olfactory Circuits in Drosophila', 2022, false, null, null, null, null);
INSERT INTO public.paper (paper_id, s2ag_json_text, created, updated, title, pub_year, key_paper, pdf_url, can_get_pdf, local_pdf_location, notes) VALUES ('eced298bed3d1d3658e057aed676bf49b033d109', '{"url": "https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/eced298bed3d1d3658e057aed676bf49b033d109", "year": 2022, "title": "Valence opponency in peripheral olfactory processing", "venue": "Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences", "authors": [{"name": "Shiuan-Tze Wu", "authorId": "10010313"}, {"name": "Jen-Yung Chen", "authorId": "2115896055"}, {"name": "V. Martin", "authorId": "2052554131"}, {"name": "Renny Ng", "authorId": "37258121"}, {"name": "Ye Zhang", "authorId": "2115893228"}, {"name": "Dhruv Grover", "authorId": "38384068"}, {"name": "R. Greenspan", "authorId": "2794356"}, {"name": "Johnatan Aljadeff", "authorId": "3219261"}, {"name": "Chih-Ying Su", "authorId": "46712902"}], "journal": {"name": "Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America", "volume": "119"}, "paperId": "eced298bed3d1d3658e057aed676bf49b033d109", "abstract": "Significance Are olfactory receptor neurons (ORNs) arranged in a functionally meaningful manner to facilitate information processing? Here, we address this long-standing question by uncovering a valence map in the olfactory periphery of Drosophila. Within sensory hairs, we find that neighboring ORNs antagonistically regulate behaviors: stereotypically compartmentalized large- and small-spike ORNs, recognized by their characteristic spike amplitudes, either promote or inhibit the same type of behavior, respectively. Systematic optogenetic and thermogenetic assays—covering the majority of antennal sensilla—highlight a valence-opponent organization. Critically, odor-mixture behavioral experiments show that lateral inhibition between antagonistic ORNs mediates robust behavioral decisions in response to countervailing cues. Computational modeling predicts that the robustness of behavioral output depends on odor mixture ratios. A hallmark of complex sensory systems is the organization of neurons into functionally meaningful maps, which allow for comparison and contrast of parallel inputs via lateral inhibition. However, it is unclear whether such a map exists in olfaction. Here, we address this question by determining the organizing principle underlying the stereotyped pairing of olfactory receptor neurons (ORNs) in Drosophila sensory hairs, wherein compartmentalized neurons inhibit each other via ephaptic coupling. Systematic behavioral assays reveal that most paired ORNs antagonistically regulate the same type of behavior. Such valence opponency is relevant in critical behavioral contexts including place preference, egg laying, and courtship. Odor-mixture experiments show that ephaptic inhibition provides a peripheral means for evaluating and shaping countervailing cues relayed to higher brain centers. Furthermore, computational modeling suggests that this organization likely contributes to processing ratio information in odor mixtures. This olfactory valence map may have evolved to swiftly process ethologically meaningful odor blends without involving costly synaptic computation.", "citations": [{"title": "Sensory neuroecology and multimodal evolution across the genus Drosophila", "paperId": "d7538153872a08c63404a9069208ef48e119c617"}, {"title": "Copy number changes in co-expressed odorant receptor genes enable selection for sensory differences in drosophilid species.", "paperId": "64af902299c277e97e3bc557b1a08ad639ab3682"}, {"title": "Odorant inhibition in mosquito olfaction mediated by inverse agonists.", "paperId": "6b6df80607ecebdbc93e229e067635933851fe90"}, {"title": "The neural basis of interspecies interactions in insects.", "paperId": "1878e2cdc650b348c72f0cae6dd8caa884eda9bf"}], "externalIds": {"DOI": "10.1073/pnas.2120134119", "PubMed": "35091473", "CorpusId": 246388232, "PubMedCentral": "8812543"}, "isOpenAccess": false, "citationCount": 4, "fieldsOfStudy": ["Medicine"], "openAccessPdf": null, "citationStyles": {"bibtex": "@[''JournalArticle'']{Wu2022ValenceOI,\n author = {Shiuan-Tze Wu and Jen-Yung Chen and V. Martin and Renny Ng and Ye Zhang and Dhruv Grover and R. Greenspan and Johnatan Aljadeff and Chih-Ying Su},\n booktitle = {Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences},\n journal = {Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America},\n title = {Valence opponency in peripheral olfactory processing},\n volume = {119},\n year = {2022}\n}\n"}, "referenceCount": 67, "publicationDate": "2022-01-28", "s2FieldsOfStudy": [{"source": "external", "category": "Medicine"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Biology"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Psychology"}], "publicationTypes": ["JournalArticle"], "publicationVenue": null, "influentialCitationCount": 0}', '2023-01-27 11:02:09.781332', '2023-01-27 11:02:09.781332', 'Valence opponency in peripheral olfactory processing', 2022, false, null, null, null, null);
