iology/"], "alternate_names": ["Plo Biology", "PLOS Biology", "PLO Biology"]}, "influentialCitationCount": 0}', '2023-01-27 11:02:46.411176', '2023-01-27 11:02:46.411176', 'Stress and odorant receptor feedback during a critical period after hatching regulates olfactory sensory neuron differentiation in Drosophila', 2021, false, null, null, null, null);
INSERT INTO public.paper (paper_id, s2ag_json_text, created, updated, title, pub_year, key_paper, pdf_url, can_get_pdf, local_pdf_location, notes) VALUES ('e1357a54a2c136dbcd63d4bca3c725e8cd63938a', '{"url": "https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/e1357a54a2c136dbcd63d4bca3c725e8cd63938a", "year": 2021, "title": "Advances in the Study of Olfaction in Eusocial Ants", "venue": "Insects", "authors": [{"name": "S. T. Ferguson", "authorId": "50426577"}, {"name": "I. Bakis", "authorId": "1475554338"}, {"name": "L. Zwiebel", "authorId": "4120896"}], "journal": {"name": "Insects", "volume": "12"}, "paperId": "e1357a54a2c136dbcd63d4bca3c725e8cd63938a", "abstract": "Simple Summary In contrast to solitary insects such as the fruit fly or mosquito, eusocial ants form colonial societies comprised of reproductives (female queens and short-lived males) and thousands of sterile female offspring known as workers. Social behaviors such as nursing the queen’s offspring, foraging for food, and nest defense emerge from the collective behavior of the workers. Importantly, these behaviors critically depend on the exchange of information through the detection of chemical cues in the environment. While research efforts have historically aimed to understand the chemical ecology of these social insects, advances in the application of molecular technology over the past decade have facilitated novel studies that bridge the gap between social behaviors and olfaction. Here, we review major advances in the study of molecular olfaction in eusocial ants and highlight potential avenues for future research. Abstract Over the past decade, spurred in part by the sequencing of the first ant genomes, there have been major advances in the field of olfactory myrmecology. With the discovery of a significant expansion of the odorant receptor gene family, considerable efforts have been directed toward understanding the olfactory basis of complex social behaviors in ant colonies. Here, we review recent pivotal studies that have begun to reveal insights into the development of the olfactory system as well as how olfactory stimuli are peripherally and centrally encoded. Despite significant biological and technical impediments, substantial progress has been achieved in the application of gene editing and other molecular techniques that notably distinguish the complex olfactory system of ants from other well-studied insect model systems, such as the fruit fly. In doing so, we hope to draw attention not only to these studies but also to critical knowledge gaps that will serve as a compass for future research endeavors.", "citations": [{"title": "Sparse and stereotyped encoding implicates a core glomerulus for ant alarm behavior", "paperId": "bf34b92167664ef9eaf460501916f1b9b9c800df"}, {"title": "Olfactory Sensitivity Aligns with Caste Revealing Multipotential Minors and Specialized Soldier Majors in Camponotus floridanus Ants", "paperId": "36c1c03d587779c9de33fc46e875069058bafeac"}, {"title": "A tropical lady beetle, Diomus lupusapudoves (Coleoptera: Coccinellidae), deceives potential enemies to predate an ant-protected coffee pest through putative chemical mimicry", "paperId": "1cf1b253d62515ffb82d03079fba025e19ae7cf9"}, {"title": "Comparative Antennal Morphometry and Sensilla Organization in the Reproductive and Non-Reproductive Castes of the Formosan Subterranean Termite", "paperId": "d43fc4ae9a39271cf5c1d18373211eefa775490a"}], "externalIds": {"DOI": "10.3390/insects12030252", "PubMed": "33802783", "CorpusId": 232381862, "PubMedCentral": "8002415"}, "isOpenAccess": true, "citationCount": 4, "fieldsOfStudy": ["Medicine"], "openAccessPdf": {"url": "https://www.mdpi.com/2075-4450/12/3/252/pdf", "status": "GOLD"}, "citationStyles": {"bibtex": "@[''Review'', ''JournalArticle'']{Ferguson2021AdvancesIT,\n author = {S. T. Ferguson and I. Bakis and L. Zwiebel},\n booktitle = {Insects},\n journal = {Insects},\n title = {Advances in the Study of Olfaction in Eusocial Ants},\n volume = {12},\n year = {2021}\n}\n"}, "referenceCount": 142, "publicationDate": "2021-03-01", "s2FieldsOfStudy": [{"source": "external", "category": "Medicine"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Biology"}], "publicationTypes": ["Review", "JournalArticle"], "publicationVenue": {"id": "2b363da1-82c9-4665-ace5-f2466f375f83", "url": "http://www.e-helvetica.nb.admin.ch/directAccess?callnumber=bel-190609", "issn": "2075-4450", "name": "Insects", "type": "journal", "alternate_urls": ["https://www.mdpi.com/journal/insects/about", "http://nbn-resolving.de/urn/resolver.pl?urn=urn:nbn:ch:bel-190609", "https://www.mdpi.com/journal/insects"]}, "influentialCitationCount": 0}', '2023-01-27 11:02:50.549355', '2023-01-27 11:02:50.549355', 'Advances in the Study of Olfaction in Eusocial Ants', 2021, false, null, null, null, null);
INSERT INTO public.paper (paper_id, s2ag_json_text, created, updated, title, pub_year, key_paper, pdf_url, can_get_pdf, local_pdf_location, notes) VALUES ('8602614803dc9805a3f3f8b16f68676941594333', '{"url": "https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/8602614803dc9805a3f3f8b16f68676941594333", "year": 2021, "title": "Olfaction in Anopheles mosquitoes.", "venue": "Chemical Sensors", "authors": [{"name": "J. Konopka", "authorId": "86922701"}, {"name": "Darya Task", "authorId": "7686107"}, {"name": "A. Afify", "authorId": "40600157"}, {"name": "J. Raji", "authorId": "31219622"}, {"name": "Kate Deibel", "authorId": "72717966"}, {"name": "Sarah E. Maguire", "authorId": "6263993"}, {"name": "Randy Lawrence", "authorId": "2080177467"}, {"name": "C. Potter", "authorId": "40574640"}], "journal": {"name": "Chemical senses"}, "paperId": "8602614803dc9805a3f3f8b16f68676941594333", "abstract": "As vectors for disease, mosquitoes are a global threat to human health. The Anopheles mosquito is the deadliest mosquito species as the insect vector for the malaria-causing parasite, which kills hundreds of thousands every year. These mosquitoes are reliant on their sense of smell (olfaction) to guide most of their behaviors, and a better understanding of Anopheles olfaction identifies opportunities for reducing the spread of malaria. This review takes a detailed look at Anopheles olfaction. We explore a range of topics from chemosensory receptors, olfactory neurons, and sensory appendages to behaviors guided by olfaction (including host-seeking, foraging, oviposition, and mating), to vector management strategies that target mosquito olfaction. We identify many research areas that remain to be addressed.", "citations": [{"title": "Humidity sensors that alert mosquitoes to nearby hosts and egg-laying sites", "paperId": "13d7e85b0b985cd69c1e0f5d6a29e04d4139d3da"}, {"title": "Neurogenetic identification of mosquito sensory neurons", "paperId": "5498a60ca06df112f06f2c99e0c173998c4ebc93"}, {"title": "Technological advances in mosquito olfaction neurogenetics.", "paperId": "574b3bc6851e8ab7694012225c582e0231d27149"}, {"title": "Mapping potential malaria vector larval habitats for larval source management: Introduction to multi-model ensembling approaches", "paperId": "71b206bbc7132992bcd1ac56d93394434d0f8ae1"}, {"title": "Chemosensory Ionotropic Receptors in Human Host-Seeking Mosquitoes.", "paperId": "61d5d5ed9b2d8aee91d070d2a2b14892c0c49580"}, {"title": "Autofluorescent Biomolecules in Diptera: From Structure to Metabolism and Behavior", "paperId": "424a9a48a951f1e95a3d435a74af48b05604dfe8"}, {"title": "Biting Innovations of Mosquito-Based Biomaterials and Medical Devices", "paperId": "ded260e3a830fbfa14f93dcb2c55d0f4526a65c6"}, {"title": "Odorant-receptor-mediated regulation of chemosensory gene expression in the malaria mosquito Anopheles gambiae", "paperId": "715c5cf74a886084cbe78154437ff7807406478e"}, {"title": "Differential mosquito attraction to humans is associated with skin-derived carboxylic acid levels", "paperId": "013253906a4fcb18e615fd51e151107b94aa12be"}, {"title": "Human attractive cues and mosquito host-seeking behavior.", "paperId": "ac05b4713a43bc11501df485ff217255438fe242"}, {"title": "Dissections of Larval, Pupal and Adult Butterfly Brains for Immunostaining and Molecular Analysis", "paperId": "50803260f83a6b18bfc4ba700d422f293fc6b8c2"}, {"title": "Unlocking pan-neuronal expression in mosquitoes", "paperId": "724a605fb41b0d26cc61dbeee48c3e2fdce456c2"}], "externalIds": {"DOI": "10.1093/chemse/bjab021", "PubMed": "33885760", "CorpusId": 233350870}, "isOpenAccess": true, "citationCount": 12, "fieldsOfStudy": ["Medicine"], "openAccessPdf": {"url": "https://academic.oup.com/chemse/article-pdf/doi/10.1093/chemse/bjab021/38864155/bjab021.pdf", "status": "BRONZE"}, "citationStyles": {"bibtex": "@[''JournalArticle'', ''Review'']{Konopka2021OlfactionIA,\n author = {J. Konopka and Darya Task and A. Afify and J. Raji and Kate Deibel and Sarah E. Mag