r.com/journal/441/"], "alternate_names": ["Cell Tissue Res"]}, "influentialCitationCount": 0}', '2023-01-27 11:20:33.734913', '2023-01-27 11:20:33.734913', 'Editorial for the special issue "Olfactory Coding and Circuitries"', 2021, false, null, null, null, null);
INSERT INTO public.paper (paper_id, s2ag_json_text, created, updated, title, pub_year, key_paper, pdf_url, can_get_pdf, local_pdf_location, notes) VALUES ('f2d84761d99eab3d143c0ac17842c48c6a959d99', '{"url": "https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/f2d84761d99eab3d143c0ac17842c48c6a959d99", "year": 2022, "title": "Generative network modeling reveals quantitative definitions of bilateral symmetry exhibited by a whole insect brain connectome", "venue": "bioRxiv", "authors": [{"name": "B. Pedigo", "authorId": "107899997"}, {"name": "Michael Powell", "authorId": "2056987231"}, {"name": "Eric W. Bridgeford", "authorId": "5470543"}, {"name": "Michael Winding", "authorId": "4144897"}, {"name": "Carey E. Priebe", "authorId": "2068800231"}, {"name": "J. Vogelstein", "authorId": "1717958"}], "journal": {"name": "bioRxiv"}, "paperId": "f2d84761d99eab3d143c0ac17842c48c6a959d99", "abstract": "Comparing connectomes can help explain how neural connectivity is related to genetics, disease, development, learning, and behavior. However, making statistical inferences about the significance and nature of differences between two networks is an open problem, and such analysis has not been extensively applied to nanoscale connectomes. Here, we investigate this problem via a case study on the bilateral symmetry of a larval Drosophila brain connectome. We translate notions of “bilateral symmetry” to generative models of the network structure of the left and right hemispheres, allowing us to test and refine our understanding of symmetry. We find significant differences in connection probabilities both across the entire left and right networks and between specific cell types. By rescaling connection probabilities or removing certain edges based on weight, we also present adjusted definitions of bilateral symmetry exhibited by this connectome. This work shows how statistical inferences from networks can inform the study of connectomes, facilitating future comparisons of neural structures.", "citations": [], "externalIds": {"DOI": "10.1101/2022.11.28.518219", "CorpusId": 254097574}, "isOpenAccess": true, "citationCount": 0, "fieldsOfStudy": ["Biology"], "openAccessPdf": {"url": "https://www.biorxiv.org/content/biorxiv/early/2022/11/28/2022.11.28.518219.full.pdf", "status": "GREEN"}, "citationStyles": {"bibtex": "@None{Pedigo2022GenerativeNM,\n author = {B. Pedigo and Michael Powell and Eric W. Bridgeford and Michael Winding and Carey E. Priebe and J. Vogelstein},\n booktitle = {bioRxiv},\n journal = {bioRxiv},\n title = {Generative network modeling reveals quantitative definitions of bilateral symmetry exhibited by a whole insect brain connectome},\n year = {2022}\n}\n"}, "referenceCount": 67, "publicationDate": "2022-11-28", "s2FieldsOfStudy": [{"source": "external", "category": "Biology"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Biology"}], "publicationTypes": null, "publicationVenue": {"id": "027ffd21-ebb0-4af8-baf5-911124292fd0", "url": "http://biorxiv.org/", "name": "bioRxiv", "type": "journal"}, "influentialCitationCount": 0}', '2023-01-27 11:20:37.356915', '2023-01-27 11:20:37.356915', 'Generative network modeling reveals quantitative definitions of bilateral symmetry exhibited by a whole insect brain connectome', 2022, false, null, null, null, null);
INSERT INTO public.paper (paper_id, s2ag_json_text, created, updated, title, pub_year, key_paper, pdf_url, can_get_pdf, local_pdf_location, notes) VALUES ('0910cb7d82c4b4f0212b06ea14e1fe5637970289', '{"url": "https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/0910cb7d82c4b4f0212b06ea14e1fe5637970289", "year": 2022, "title": "The connectome of an insect brain", "venue": "bioRxiv", "authors": [{"name": "Michael Winding", "authorId": "4144897"}, {"name": "B. Pedigo", "authorId": "107899997"}, {"name": "Christopher L. Barnes", "authorId": "2054842872"}, {"name": "Heather G. Patsolic", "authorId": "52606257"}, {"name": "Youngser Park", "authorId": "6770837"}, {"name": "Tom Kazimiers", "authorId": "6930811"}, {"name": "Akira Fushiki", "authorId": "4322468"}, {"name": "Ingrid V. Andrade", "authorId": "90184932"}, {"name": "Avinash Khandelwal", "authorId": "50022871"}, {"name": "Javier Valdes-Aleman", "authorId": "1401887699"}, {"name": "Feng Li", "authorId": "2146311675"}, {"name": "N. Randel", "authorId": "4058766"}, {"name": "Elizabeth Barsotti", "authorId": "2192713014"}, {"name": "Ana Correia", "authorId": "2192740823"}, {"name": "R. Fetter", "authorId": "2596869"}, {"name": "V. Hartenstein", "authorId": "2204140"}, {"name": "Carey E. Priebe", "authorId": "2068800231"}, {"name": "J. Vogelstein", "authorId": "1717958"}, {"name": "Albert Cardona", "authorId": "2122284027"}, {"name": "Marta Zlatic", "authorId": "1692863"}], "journal": {"name": "bioRxiv"}, "paperId": "0910cb7d82c4b4f0212b06ea14e1fe5637970289", "abstract": "Brains contain networks of interconnected neurons, so knowing the network architecture is essential for understanding brain function. We therefore mapped the synaptic-resolution connectome of an insect brain (Drosophila larva) with rich behavior, including learning, value-computation, and action-selection, comprising 3,013 neurons and 544,000 synapses. We characterized neuron-types, hubs, feedforward and feedback pathways, and cross-hemisphere and brain-nerve cord interactions. We found pervasive multisensory and interhemispheric integration, highly recurrent architecture, abundant feedback from descending neurons, and multiple novel circuit motifs. The brain’s most recurrent circuits comprised the input and output neurons of the learning center. Some structural features, including multilayer shortcuts and nested recurrent loops, resembled powerful machine learning architectures. The identified brain architecture provides a basis for future experimental and theoretical studies of neural circuits. One-Sentence Summary We generated a synaptic-resolution brain connectome and characterized its connection types, neuron types, and circuit motifs.", "citations": [{"title": "Tools for comprehensive reconstruction and analysis of Drosophila motor circuits", "paperId": "1e124b9f834d9f48c547f90650a9fcd5e9e071f8"}], "externalIds": {"DOI": "10.1101/2022.11.28.516756", "CorpusId": 254070919}, "isOpenAccess": true, "citationCount": 1, "fieldsOfStudy": ["Biology"], "openAccessPdf": {"url": "https://www.biorxiv.org/content/biorxiv/early/2022/11/28/2022.11.28.516756.full.pdf", "status": "GREEN"}, "citationStyles": {"bibtex": "@None{Winding2022TheCO,\n author = {Michael Winding and B. Pedigo and Christopher L. Barnes and Heather G. Patsolic and Youngser Park and Tom Kazimiers and Akira Fushiki and Ingrid V. Andrade and Avinash Khandelwal and Javier Valdes-Aleman and Feng Li and N. Randel and Elizabeth Barsotti and Ana Correia and R. Fetter and V. Hartenstein and Carey E. Priebe and J. Vogelstein and Albert Cardona and Marta Zlatic},\n booktitle = {bioRxiv},\n journal = {bioRxiv},\n title = {The connectome of an insect brain},\n year = {2022}\n}\n"}, "referenceCount": 211, "publicationDate": "2022-11-28", "s2FieldsOfStudy": [{"source": "external", "category": "Biology"}, {"source": "s2-fos-model", "category": "Biology"}], "publicationTypes": null, "publicationVenue": {"id": "027ffd21-ebb0-4af8-baf5-911124292fd0", "url": "http://biorxiv.org/", "name": "bioRxiv", "type": "journal"}, "influentialCitationCount": 0}', '2023-01-27 11:20:40.963717', '2023-01-27 11:20:40.963717', 'The connectome of an insect brain', 2022, false, null, null, null, null);
